<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>HEAT VENTILATION AIR CONDITIONING (HVAC), Orifice Tube System, Pre-March 2007 - 3200, 4100, 4200, 4300,
        4400, 7300, 7400, 7500, 7600, 7700, 8500, 8600 - TROUBLESHOOTING QUICK TIPS - BEFORE YOU CALL TECH SERVICES
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl1602571" graphiccount="0">
        <title>BEFORE YOU CALL TECH SERVICES</title>
        <para>If, after performing the troubleshooting procedures in
            <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602541.xml" xrefid="hl1602541">SECTION 5</hotlnk>
            <xref refid="hl1602541"/>
            and reviewing the information in this section, the HVAC system is still not performing correctly, proceed
            with the following steps.
            <emph type="bold">(Record all measurements and indications. These may be helpful to Technical Services if
                they are contacted.)
            </emph>
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>To perform the following steps, the engine and A/C system must NOT have been run within the last
                    30 minutes. The temperature of the A/C system MUST BE approximately the same as the ambient
                    temperature.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">With the engine off, connect a recovery station (with an internal gauge set) to the low and
                high side A/C service ports. A known good, manual, manifold gauge set may also be used. Refer to
                <hotlnk document="s16025_53.xml" xrefid="f1602539">Figure 41</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="f1602539"/>
                and/or
                <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602528.xml" xrefid="f1602541">Figure 43</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="f1602541"/>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To determine if the A/C system is undercharged; or, if there is air or a non-condensable gas
                in the A/C system:
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Determine (and record) the ambient temperature (within a degree or two).</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Record the system pressures indicated on the high and low gauges connected to the A/C
                    system. Both gauges should read close to the same value when the truck is not running.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Compare the pressure readings recorded in the last step to the pressures shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="t1602549">TABLE 46</hotlnk>. (The table is part of the Performance AC Chart
                    TMT-3416.)
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If the pressure on the gauges is more than 10 psig higher than the pressure listed in
                    the chart, the A/C system contains air or some non-condensable gas in the refrigerant system. The
                    system needs to be discharged, evacuated, and recharged using a recovery system. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602547.xml" xrefid="hl1602547">SECTION 7</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="hl1602547"/>.
                </para>
                <para>EXAMPLE: If the ambient is 75&#176;F, the A/C system pressure should be in the 78-79 psig range.
                    If the pressure is 90 psig or higher it indicates that there is air or some non-condensable gas in
                    the system.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>A refrigerant identifier can also be used to verify the contents of the A/C system. Refer
                            to
                            <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602572.xml" xrefid="hl1602572">SECTION 7.3</hotlnk>
                            <xref refid="hl1602572"/>.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If the pressure on the gauges is more than 10 psig lower than the pressure listed in the
                    chart, the system is undercharged. The system needs to be discharged, evacuated, and recharged using
                    a recovery system. Undercharged systems should be inspected for a possible leak before being
                    discharged. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602547.xml" xrefid="hl1602547">SECTION 7</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="hl1602547"/>.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Connect the EZ-Tech service tool to the vehicle's diagnostic connector.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To evaluate the A/C system performance using the diagnostic program, perform the following
                steps:
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Without starting the engine, turn the ignition key ON.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Open the diagnostic program.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Set the program to monitor the following signals, then record their values:</para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>the A/C Input Temp Sensor (thermistor)</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>the A/C Output Temp Sensor (thermistor)</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>the A/C Pressure Sensor (transducer).</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">From the gauges connected to the A/C system, record the system pressures.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Set the HVAC Mode control to the Normal A/C position. Using the diagnostic program,
                    monitor and record the A/C Request signal while switching the HVAC Fan control between OFF and any
                    other position. The A/C Request signal should be OFF when the Fan control is OFF, and ON when the
                    Fan control is in any other position. If the signal is not functioning correctly, refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602560.xml" xrefid="hl1602560">SECTION 9</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="hl1602560"/>
                    to troubleshoot the circuit.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If the recorded thermistor values are not within 5 degrees of each other, refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602566.xml" xrefid="hl1602566">TABLE 10</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="t1602511"/>
                    to troubleshoot the circuit.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If the recorded pressure transducer value is not within 20 psig of the gauges, refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602567.xml" xrefid="hl1602567">SECTION 16</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="hl1602567"/>
                    to troubleshoot the circuit.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
